ked. We may need to create or modify an existing test. The active class one-to-one mapping indicates a dedicated file, which is currently untracked but should be included. There could be a naming mismatch since the rule suggests using \\\"Inner\\\" plus the name for inner variables. For `$_newFilterContext_closure13`, I’ll rename it to `Inner_new...` with an underscore, as the existing pattern does.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing MethodHandle issues**\\n\\nI need to figure out why I'm encountering a failure. It could be that `MethodHandles.privateLookupIn` can't access a package-private static method due to the test class being in an unnamed module, along with rest-assured being in an automatic module. If the test fails, I wonder if the report won’t show newly covered code. I should avoid using MethodHandle; maybe direct reflection could work better. \\n\\nLastly, I need to check if the active class is in the rest-assured jar and if `Class.forName` is properly intercepting the closure class initialization.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating Class.forName issues**\\n\\nI think there’s a potential issue with `Class.forName` being called on `\\\"io.restassured.internal.RequestSpecificationImpl\\\"` if that class is already initialized. Despite being covered, maybe the exact call to MethodHandle isn’t executed because the test method throws a Throwable, and it seems JUnit doesn't catch that. I should check if the dynamic coverage is mapping the class name correctly, especially since the test file is named `Inner_newFilterContext_closure13Test`. I'll need to inspect the include patterns in build.gradle.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_yCRwh8WBtdf3t88Kosdo0p6d|fc_06a8b289e22fc917016a27779e40288193b51ee40ba7654483", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/build.gradle", "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 364